data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Inventory

| Location | API | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|---|
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control-flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | Blind wait | `Thread.Join(timeout)` |

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime **cannot** forcibly inject exceptions into threads. Your `Stop()` method will crash, and the `ThreadAbortException` catch block will never execute, meaning `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` is dead code.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent to the old ThreadAbortException catch —
                // cancellation was requested, clean up partial work.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The loop condition will exit
                // naturally on the next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // cooperative signal — replaces Thread.Abort

        // Join with timeout replaces Thread.Sleep(2000) + Abort.
        // If the thread doesn't exit in 2s, it means GetNextItem or
        // ProcessItem isn't respecting the token — fix those methods.
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Log a warning — there is no safe forced-kill equivalent.
            // The thread will exit when it next checks the token.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes You Must Also Make

**`GetNextItem` must accept and respect the token.** If it blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection` or I/O), it will never see cancellation otherwise:

```csharp
// Before — blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could break it
private Item GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

// After — wakes up immediately on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep` or `WaitHandle.WaitOne`:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep(ms) with:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms);

// Replace event.WaitOne() with:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle });
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Token not passed through call chain** | If `GetNextItem` blocks without the token, `Cancel()` has no effect and `Join(2000)` will time out every time. Every blocking method in the chain must accept the token. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` ignores tokens** | `Thread.Sleep(n)` cannot be cancelled. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(n)`. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` leak** | `CTS` is `IDisposable`. Implement `IDisposable` on the processor (shown above) and dispose it. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation. Without it, you'd accidentally swallow unrelated cancellations. |
| **No forced kill exists** | If the thread truly can't cooperate (e.g., stuck in native code), the only option is to move that work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`. |
| **`ResetAbort` pattern** | The old code used `ResetAbort` so the loop could continue and `finally` would run. With cooperative cancellation, the loop naturally exits via the `while` condition — no special reset is needed. |
